annotations: But the end is closer every second than it’s ever been

This relates back to a lyric in the beginning of the song:

“And I am older every second than I’ve ever been”

The first one is more lighthearted while in this one the singer realizes that, although their life is continuing, it only means that the end is becoming closer and closer.
In this line, Ambrosia is personified. Perhaps “Ambrosia” is a pseudonym for a person that the singer likes. This person is changing the singer’s personality for the better.

I want you more with every second than I ever did
 Right now, and now, and now
They are singing to someone, expressing their admiration and love.
Gets covered in Cool Whip, shoved to the back of the fridge
You have to chill ambrosia in the fridge for several houses in order to get the dish to set properly.
I check my balance as I lean to one side
Another line with dual meanings: to “check my balance” refers both to look at the amount of money in Tucker’s checking account and to balance whilst leaning to the side.

Chewing on my fat lip, contemplate the Cool Whip
 “Cover dish and chill for a while”

In this line, Tucker is looking at a dish of ambrosia, which is typically served with cool whip.

Here, “chill” has two meanings: to both relax for a while and to refrigerate the covered dish (a very important step in making ambrosia).

Ambrosia is an American variety of fruit salad, which  usually include a variety of fruits, mini marshmallows, and coconut; variations of the recipe may also include whipped cream/Cool Whip (as well as other dairy products).

In ancient Greek myths, ambrosia refers to the food and drink consumed the gods which can confer immortality (not a fruit salad, in this case).

Ducking out of cool rain, listening to Coltrane
 I grew up the place where she died
Alice Coltrane died in Los Angeles, California – Tucker’s hometown, and the place where they went to college.

description.plain:
“‘Gay Bar’ celebrates the incredible spectrum of characters dressed to impress at your average regional queer watering hole,” Tucker explains. “I’m aiming for innocence & bliss here — the joy of looking really good & dancing with people who already like you a lot.”

description.plain:
Rosie Tucker released this cover of Jeffrey Lewis’ “Arrow,” (from the 2003 album It’s The Ones Who’ve Cracked That The Light Shines Through.)

This is the third track released by Tucker since their sophomore album, Never Not Never Not Never Not, in 2019.
